# @PROJECT_NAME@

STM32 @STM32_CHIP@ project on stm32-sdk @SDK_VERSION@ — bare-metal I2C bus
scanner that prints every responding address over USART2.

## SDK rules (must follow)

- CMSIS only, HAL/LL forbidden.
- C++20 (gnu++20), C11 (gnu11).
- MMIO access through `driver::reg::set/clear/write/read/get/modify` only.
- No raw pointers to peripherals — references (`GPIO_TypeDef&`).
- Configs without defaults — every field must be explicit.
- `GpioConfig` is an aggregate; wrap in `gpio({...})` for compile-time validation.
- Trailing comma after the last designated initializer to keep clang-format multi-line.

## Build / flash

```bash
stmtool build --native
stmtool flash
stmtool sdk update          # if [sdk] version = "develop"
```

## SDK reference

- Documentation: <https://khosta77.github.io/stm32-sdk/>
- I2C driver: <https://khosta77.github.io/stm32-sdk/modules/drivers/#i2c-driverstm32f4i2c>

## This template

Sweeps I2C addresses `0x03..0x77` once per cycle and prints any device that
ACKs. Useful when an OLED / sensor module has unreadable silkscreen and you
need to find its address.

**No FreeRTOS** — calling `I2c::probe()` before `vTaskStartScheduler()` hangs
on the internal mutex; the template stays bare-metal to avoid that.

### Pinout

| Function | Pin | Notes |
|----------|-----|-------|
| I2C1 SCL | PB6 | AF4, open-drain, pull-up |
| I2C1 SDA | PB7 | AF4, open-drain, pull-up |
| USART2 TX | PA2 | AF7 |
| USART2 RX | PA3 | AF7 (not used) |

I2C clock: 100 kHz (Standard Mode). UART: 115200 baud, 8N1.

### Expected serial output

```
=== I2C1 scan (PB6/PB7 @ 100 kHz) ===
  found device at 7-bit 0x3C (8-bit write 0x78 / read 0x79)
  found device at 7-bit 0x68 (8-bit write 0xD0 / read 0xD1)
scan complete: 2 device(s)
```

If your OLED is at `0x3D` or your IMU is at `0x69`, this template tells you
immediately. Full sweep completes in under 200 ms (the I2C driver races
ADDR vs AF for fast NACK detection).

### How to verify

1. Connect an FTDI USB-UART to PA2/GND at 115200 baud.
2. Open the serial port: `screen /dev/tty.usbserial-* 115200` (macOS) or
   `minicom -D /dev/ttyUSB0 -b 115200` (Linux).
3. Reset the board.
4. The scan output prints once per few seconds.

If nothing prints, verify:
- The I2C bus has pull-ups (usually built into the sensor module).
- Power to the slave is 3.3 V.
- USART2 is enabled in `__initialize_hardware()`.
